# PunchMe — Project Memory

## What Is This

PunchMe is a party game for friends played in the browser. Players are joined by 1–2 AI bots. Everyone receives the beginning of a joke and must write a funny ending. The number of joke prompts equals the number of players, and each player gets 2 prompts. Players who share the same prompt compete head-to-head, and the rest of the group votes for the funnier punchline.

## How the Game Works

1. A host creates a room and configures the number of bot players (1–2).
2. Other players join by entering the room code.
3. If the total player count is odd at game start, an extra bot is added automatically.
4. **Writing phase:** Each player receives 2 unfinished prompts. For N players there are N distinct prompts, distributed in a circular pattern so each prompt is assigned to exactly 2 players.
5. **Voting phase:** Duels are formed per prompt — the two players who share a prompt compete. Other players vote for the funnier punchline. Duel participants cannot vote on their own duel. Bots vote automatically.
6. **Rating phase:** All players rate jokes on a 1–10 scale. Rating is optional — empty submissions are allowed. The phase advances immediately when all human players submit.
7. **Scoreboard** is shown after each round. Multiple rounds can be played.

## Tech Stack

- **Backend:** NestJS, Socket.IO, Mongoose (MongoDB), Zod, class-validator
- **Frontend:** React 19, Vite 8, Socket.IO client
- **AI:** Ollama in Docker (`ollama` service), `huihui_ai/qwen2.5-abliterate:1.5b` (Russian, uncensored, ~30 tok/s on CPU), nomic-embed-text (embeddings); API uses `OLLAMA_BASE_URL=http://ollama:11434` by default in Compose.
- **Infra:** Docker Compose, ngrok, PowerShell scripts
- **Language:** TypeScript (strict), Russian UI, English code

## Architecture

```
api/src/modules/
├── game/        — rooms, rounds, duels, voting, ratings, bot orchestration (WebSocket gateway + service)
├── ai/             — Ollama chat requests, prompt generation, bot answer generation, prompt templates
├── prompt-starter/ — MongoDB-backed prompt starters with seed data, N² random selection, and background AI generation
├── joke-memory/    — joke storage in MongoDB, quality scoring, retrieval for few-shot examples, finetune dataset export
├── embedding/      — text embeddings via Ollama (nomic-embed-text)

web/src/
├── App.tsx              — main UI for all game phases
├── hooks/use-game-client.ts — game state, session, socket actions
├── socket/game-socket.ts    — Socket.IO client wrapper
├── models/              — shared client types (mirrored from API)
```

Module dependency graph: `GameModule` → `AiModule`, `PromptStarterModule`, `JokeMemoryModule` → `EmbeddingModule`.

## Key Implementation Details

- Game state is fully server-authoritative. Votes, submission status, and phase transitions are driven by the server and broadcast via Socket.IO; `gameState` is emitted per connected socket so duel vote tallies stay hidden until a voter has cast a vote (duel participants always receive full tallies).
- Each room accumulates `usedPromptTexts` across rounds so unfinished joke openings are not reused in later rounds; AI and local fallback generation both respect this exclusion list.
- Bot answers are generated via Ollama with a 90s timeout ceiling (effective deadline is the 45s writing phase) and a local fallback punchline.
- Prompt starters are stored in MongoDB (`prompt_starters` collection) with a `usedCount` field; selection uses N² sampling (sort by usedCount, take N², then random N) to balance freshness and variety.
- On startup, the `PromptStarterService` seeds 48 Russian joke openings if the collection is empty; after each round, new prompts are generated by AI in the background and deduplicated via `normalizePromptIdentity`.
- Joke memory stores every joke (human + bot) with votes, ratings, and prompt embeddings. Top-quality examples are retrieved as few-shot context for bot answer generation.
- Prompt assignment uses a circular algorithm: player i gets prompts [i, (i+1) % N]. Duels are created per prompt between the two assigned players.
- The finetune dataset service can export JSONL for model fine-tuning, but this pipeline is not yet wired to HTTP endpoints or cron.
- Docker Compose defines: `ollama`, api, web, mongo, model-pull (profile: setup), ngrok (profile: tunnel); Ollama models persist in volume `punchme-ollama-data`.
- `npm run start:all` launches the full stack including ngrok and prints the public URL.

## Known Limitations and Weak Points

- Joke memory queue is in-memory — records are lost on container restart.
- Retrieval scans only the 600 most recent jokes; older high-quality jokes are unreachable.
- Bot style (sarcastic/chaotic/dark/absurd/bold) is chosen randomly with no feedback loop.
- Bot win-rate metrics are logged but not persisted or used for adaptation.
- Fine-tune pipeline and model versioning exist in code but are not connected to any trigger.
- No negative examples in few-shot prompts — the bot only sees what worked, not what failed.
- Embedding model versioning is not enforced at retrieval time.

